&gt;&gt; Subject: RE: Request for Feedback: Slide Deck for June 10 Seminar<=
br>
&gt;&gt; Hello Tony,<br>
&gt;&gt; Thank you for sharing the file.&nbsp; Main feedback<br>
&gt;&gt; I noticed a gap between the problem definition logic (section 2) a=
nd the AI tool selection logic (section 3) =E2=80=93 they appear to be oper=
ating at different levels of abstraction. Please correct me if I=E2=80=99m =
wrong.<br>
&gt;&gt; The current problem definition template and the resulting problem =
examples (slide 14) are outcome-oriented and sit at a strategic level, but =
AI tools function at the tactical level. A single AI tool cannot solve the =
multifaceted example problems on slide
 14. A tool can be matched to a task, not to the abstract problem or the so=
lution itself =E2=80=93 this actually shows up in slide 25 where the tool i=
s being aligned with a task, not a problem. Asking participants to go direc=
tly from problem to tool seems to skip over
 a critical step in the reasoning process.<br>
&gt;&gt; You can see the slides switch between levels of abstraction on:<br=
>
&gt;&gt;&nbsp; &nbsp; =E2=80=A2 Slide 13 =C3=A0 Problem<br>
&gt;&gt;&nbsp; &nbsp; =E2=80=A2 Slide 25 =C3=A0 Task<br>
&gt;&gt;&nbsp; &nbsp; =E2=80=A2 Slide 31 =C3=A0 Problem<br>
&gt;&gt; To strengthen the guidance regarding how to choose an appropriate =
AI tool, I suggest inserting an intermediate step where we identify a plaus=
ible solution to the defined problem and then break that solution into a se=
t of tasks. At this level we can match
 tools to tasks. The flow would go: problem =C3=A0 solution =C3=A0 tasks =
=C3=A0 tools. I think this will help participants bridge the gap between th=
e problem definition and tool selection.<br>
&gt;&gt;&nbsp; Other feedback<br>
&gt;&gt; I understand that the problem definition template on slide 14 is m=
eant to be a quick tool to move participants forward. That said, I have two=
 comments:<br>
&gt;&gt;&nbsp; &nbsp; =E2=80=A2 Consider replacing the word =E2=80=9Cconstr=
aints=E2=80=9D with the word =E2=80=9Cobstacle=E2=80=9D for the 3rd bullet =
on slide 13 (=E2=80=9CA problem defines the need, context, and the constrai=
nts=E2=80=9D). Obstacle is present in the template but there is nothing abo=
ut constraints in the template
 =E2=80=93 this makes the two slides misaligned in my view. Context is also=
 poorly explored in the template but I think going deep into the context is=
 not important for the purposes of the workshop.<br>
&gt;&gt;&nbsp; &nbsp; =E2=80=A2 Consider building on Wedell-Wedellsborg=E2=
=80=99s reframing step to include guidance to challenging assumptions about=
 the problem to ensure we=E2=80=99re solving the right problem. This can he=
lp avoid a solution-first approach instead of a problem-first one.<br>
&gt;&gt;&nbsp; My best,<br>
